<mods xmlns="http://www.loc.gov/mods/v3" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" ID="Strickmann1982" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.loc.gov/mods/v3 http://data.stonesutras.org:8080/exist/servlet/db/schema/mods-3-0.xsd"><titleInfo lang="en"><title>India in the Chinese Looking-Glass</title></titleInfo><titleInfo type="reference"><title>Strickmann 1982</title></titleInfo><name xmlns:ns2="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" ns2:href="#strickmann" type="personal"><namePart lang="en" type="family">Strickmann</namePart><namePart lang="en" type="given">Michel</namePart><role><roleTerm>author</roleTerm></role></name><abstract>In Chengdu in 971, the first printing of the Buddhist canon was initiated. this printed canon probably arrived at Dunhuang not long after the year 1000. 
    For that reason, "two imperially-commissioned manuscript sets of the Chinese Buddhist Canon, each presented to a great Dunhuang monastery during the Tang (Fujieda 1981)" had to change location. 
    Strickmann assumes that "cave 17 appears to have originally been intended as [their] ... honourable repository".</abstract><relatedItem xmlns:oXygen2="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" type="host" oXygen2:href="#KlimburgSalter1982"><titleInfo lang="en"><title>The Silk Route and the Diamond Path</title></titleInfo><name xmlns:ns2="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" ns2:href="#klimburg-salter" type="personal"><namePart lang="en" type="family">Klimburg-Salter</namePart><namePart lang="en" type="given">Deborah</namePart><role><roleTerm>editor</roleTerm></role></name><originInfo><publisher><name type="corporate"><namePart lang="en">UCLA Art Council</namePart></name></publisher><place><placeTerm>Los Angeles</placeTerm></place><dateIssued>1982</dateIssued><issuance>monographic</issuance></originInfo><part><extent unit="page"><start>53</start><end>63</end></extent></part></relatedItem></mods>